 "ce:initials": "S.", "@_fa": "true", "@type": "auth", "ce:surname": "Sooksai", "@auid": "36025849300", "ce:indexed-name": "Sooksai S."}, {"ce:given-name": "Kentaro", "preferred-name": {"ce:given-name": "Kentaro", "ce:initials": "K.", "ce:surname": "Kodama", "ce:indexed-name": "Kodama K."}, "@seq": "5", "ce:initials": "K.", "@_fa": "true", "@type": "auth", "ce:surname": "Kodama", "@auid": "55648171800", "ce:indexed-name": "Kodama K."}, {"ce:given-name": "Nuttha", "preferred-name": {"ce:given-name": "Nuttha", "ce:initials": "N.", "ce:surname": "Thongchul", "ce:indexed-name": "Thongchul N."}, "@seq": "6", "ce:initials": "N.", "@_fa": "true", "@type": "auth", "ce:surname": "Thongchul", "@auid": "12789478000", "ce:indexed-name": "Thongchul N."}]}], "citation-title": "Manipulating pyruvate decarboxylase by addition of enzyme regulators during fermentation of rhizopus oryzae to enhance lactic acid production", "abstracts": "\u00a9 2014, Springer Science+Business Media New York.Ethanol was found as the major by-product in lactate fermentation by Rhizopus oryzae. Several methods have been conducted in order to limit ethanol formation, thus increasing the lactate yield. The direct way to suppress ethanol production can be done by inhibition of the responsible enzymes in the related pathway. Pyruvate decarboxylase (PDC) and alcohol dehydrogenase (ADH) are responsible for ethanol production in R. oryzae. Shunting the ethanol production pathway by targeting at PDC was attempted in this study. Three compounds including 4-methylpyrazole, glyoxylic acid, and 3-hydroxypyruvate with the in vitro reversible inhibitory effect on PDC were selected from the literature and were used to regulate the living cell of R. oryzae during the fermentation. The results show that 0.1 mM 4-methylpyrazole of which the structure resembled a thiazolium ring in thiamine diphosphate, PDC cofactor, and 1.0 \u00b5m 3-hydroxypyruvate, pyruvate analog, effectively hampered ethanol production. Further observation on the enzyme expression indicated that these two regulators not only targeted PDC but also caused changes in ADH and lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) activities. This was perhaps due to the living cell of R. oryzae that responded to the presence of the regulators to balance the pyruvate flux and subsequently maintain its metabolic activities.", "correspondence": {"affiliation": {"country": "Thailand", "@country": "tha", "city": "Bangkok", "organization": [{"$": "Institute of Biotechnology and Genetic Engineering"}, {"$": "Chulalongkorn University"}]}, "person": {"ce:given-name": "Nuttha", "ce:initials": "N.", "ce:surname": "Thongchul", "ce:indexed-name": "Thongchul N."}}, "citation-info": {"author-keywords": {"author-keyword": [{"$": "Alcohol dehydrogenase", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Competitive inhibition", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Ethanol", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Fermentation", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Lactate dehydrogenase", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Lactic acid", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Pyruvate decarboxylase", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Rhizopus oryzae", "@xml:lang": "eng"}]}, "citation-type": {"@code": "ar"}, "citation-language": {"@language": "English", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, "abstract-language": {"@language": "English", "@xml:lang": "eng"}}, "source": {"sourcetitle-abbrev": "Appl. Biochem. Biotechnol.", "website": {"ce:e-address": {"$": "http://www.springer.com/humana+press/journal/12010", "@type": "email"}}, "@country": "usa", "translated-sourcetitle": {"$": "Applied Biochemistry and Biotechnology", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, "issn": [{"$": "15590291", "@type": "electronic"}, {"$": "02732289", "@type": "print"}], "volisspag": {"voliss": {"@volume": "174", "@issue": "5"}, "pagerange": {"@first": "1795", "@last": "1809"}}, "@type": "j", "publicationyear": {"@first": "2014"}, "publisher": {"publishername": "Humana Press Inc."}, "sourcetitle": "Applied Biochemistry and Biotechnology", "@srcid": "110291", "publicationdate": {"month": "11", "year": "